dpkg(1)                                   dpkg suite                                   dpkg(1)

NNAAMMEE
       dpkg - package manager for Debian

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       ddppkkgg [_o_p_t_i_o_n...] _a_c_t_i_o_n

WWAARRNNIINNGG
       This manual is intended for users wishing to understand ddppkkgg's command line options and
       package states in more detail than that provided by ddppkkgg ----hheellpp.

       It should _n_o_t be used by package  maintainers  wishing  to  understand  how  ddppkkgg  will
       install their packages. The descriptions of what ddppkkgg does when installing and removing
       packages are particularly inadequate.

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       ddppkkgg is a tool to install, build, remove and manage Debian packages.  The  primary  and
       more  user-friendly  front-end  for  ddppkkgg  is  aappttiittuuddee(1).  ddppkkgg  itself is controlled
       entirely via command line parameters, which consist of exactly one action and  zero  or
       more  options.  The  action-parameter  tells  ddppkkgg  what  to do and options control the
       behavior of the action in some way.

       ddppkkgg can also be used as a front-end to ddppkkgg--ddeebb(1)  and  ddppkkgg--qquueerryy(1).  The  list  of
       supported  actions  can be found later on in the AACCTTIIOONNSS section. If any such action is
       encountered ddppkkgg just runs ddppkkgg--ddeebb or ddppkkgg--qquueerryy with the parameters given to it,  but
       no  specific options are currently passed to them, to use any such option the back-ends
       need to be called directly.

IINNFFOORRMMAATTIIOONN AABBOOUUTT PPAACCKKAAGGEESS
       ddppkkgg maintains some usable information about available  packages.  The  information  is
       divided in three classes: ssttaatteess, sseelleeccttiioonn ssttaatteess and ffllaaggss. These values are intended
       to be changed mainly with ddsseelleecctt.

   PPaacckkaaggee ssttaatteess
       nnoott--iinnssttaalllleedd
              The package is not installed on your system.

       ccoonnffiigg--ffiilleess
              Only the configuration files of the package exist on the system.

       hhaallff--iinnssttaalllleedd
              The installation of the package has been started, but  not  completed  for  some
              reason.

       uunnppaacckkeedd
              The package is unpacked, but not configured.

       hhaallff--ccoonnffiigguurreedd
              The  package  is  unpacked  and  configuration  has  been  started,  but not yet
              completed for some reason.

       ttrriiggggeerrss--aawwaaiitteedd
              The package awaits trigger processing by another package.

       ttrriiggggeerrss--ppeennddiinngg
              The package has been triggered.

       iinnssttaalllleedd
              The package is correctly unpacked and configured.

   PPaacckkaaggee sseelleeccttiioonn ssttaatteess
       iinnssttaallll
              The package is selected for installation.

       hhoolldd   A package marked to be on hhoolldd is not handled by ddppkkgg, unless forced to do  that
              with option ----ffoorrccee--hhoolldd.

       ddeeiinnssttaallll
              The  package  is  selected for deinstallation (i.e. we want to remove all files,
              except configuration files).

       ppuurrggee  The package is selected to be purged (i.e. we want  to  remove  everything  from
              system directories, even configuration files).

       uunnkknnoowwnn
              The  package  selection  is  unknown.  A package that is also in a nnoott--iinnssttaalllleedd
              state, and with an ookk flag will be forgotten in the next database store.

   PPaacckkaaggee ffllaaggss
       ookk     A package marked ookk is in a known state, but might need further processing.

       rreeiinnssttrreeqq
              A package marked rreeiinnssttrreeqq is broken and requires reinstallation. These packages
              cannot be removed, unless forced with option ----ffoorrccee--rreemmoovvee--rreeiinnssttrreeqq.

AACCTTIIOONNSS
       --ii, ----iinnssttaallll _p_a_c_k_a_g_e_-_f_i_l_e...
              Install the package. If ----rreeccuurrssiivvee or --RR option is specified, _p_a_c_k_a_g_e_-_f_i_l_e must
              refer to a directory instead.

              Installation consists of the following steps:

              11.. Extract the control files of the new package.

              22.. If another  version  of  the  same  package  was  installed  before  the  new
              installation, execute _p_r_e_r_m script of the old package.

              33.. Run _p_r_e_i_n_s_t script, if provided by the package.

              44..  Unpack the new files, and at the same time back up the old files, so that if
              something goes wrong, they can be restored.

              55.. If another  version  of  the  same  package  was  installed  before  the  new
              installation,  execute  the  _p_o_s_t_r_m  script  of  the old package. Note that this
              script is executed after the _p_r_e_i_n_s_t script of  the  new  package,  because  new
              files are written at the same time old files are removed.

              66..  Configure  the  package.  See ----ccoonnffiigguurree for detailed information about how
              this is done.

       ----uunnppaacckk _p_a_c_k_a_g_e_-_f_i_l_e...
              Unpack the package, but don't configure it.  If  ----rreeccuurrssiivvee  or  --RR  option  is
              specified, _p_a_c_k_a_g_e_-_f_i_l_e must refer to a directory instead.

       ----ccoonnffiigguurree _p_a_c_k_a_g_e...|--aa|----ppeennddiinngg
              Configure  a  package  which has been unpacked but not yet configured.  If --aa or
              ----ppeennddiinngg is given instead of _p_a_c_k_a_g_e, all unpacked  but  unconfigured  packages
              are configured.

              To   reconfigure   a   package  which  has  already  been  configured,  try  the
              ddppkkgg--rreeccoonnffiigguurree(8) command instead.

              Configuring consists of the following steps:

              11.. Unpack the conffiles, and at the same time back up the old conffiles, so that
              they can be restored if something goes wrong.

              22.. Run _p_o_s_t_i_n_s_t script, if provided by the package.

       ----ttrriiggggeerrss--oonnllyy _p_a_c_k_a_g_e...|--aa|----ppeennddiinngg
              Processes  only  triggers  (since  dpkg  1.14.17).  All pending triggers will be
              processed.  If package names are supplied only those packages' triggers will  be
              processed,  exactly  once  each  where  necessary.  Use of this option may leave
              packages in the improper ttrriiggggeerrss--aawwaaiitteedd and ttrriiggggeerrss--ppeennddiinngg states. This  can
              be fixed later by running: ddppkkgg ----ccoonnffiigguurree ----ppeennddiinngg.

       --rr, ----rreemmoovvee _p_a_c_k_a_g_e...|--aa|----ppeennddiinngg
              Remove an installed package.  This removes everything except conffiles and other
              data cleaned up by the _p_o_s_t_r_m script, which may avoid having to reconfigure  the
              package  if  it is reinstalled later (conffiles are configuration files that are
              listed in the _D_E_B_I_A_N_/_c_o_n_f_f_i_l_e_s control file).  If there is  no  _D_E_B_I_A_N_/_c_o_n_f_f_i_l_e_s
              control  file  nor  _D_E_B_I_A_N_/_p_o_s_t_r_m  script, this command is equivalent to calling
              ----ppuurrggee.  If --aa or ----ppeennddiinngg is given  instead  of  a  package  name,  then  all
              packages  unpacked,  but  marked to be removed in file _/_v_a_r_/_l_i_b_/_d_p_k_g_/_s_t_a_t_u_s, are
              removed.

              Removing of a package consists of the following steps:

              11.. Run _p_r_e_r_m script

              22.. Remove the installed files

              33.. Run _p_o_s_t_r_m script

       --PP, ----ppuurrggee _p_a_c_k_a_g_e...|--aa|----ppeennddiinngg
              Purge  an  installed  or  already  removed  package.  This  removes  everything,
              including  conffiles,  and  anything  else  cleaned  up  from  _p_o_s_t_r_m.  If --aa or
              ----ppeennddiinngg is given instead of a package name,  then  all  packages  unpacked  or
              removed, but marked to be purged in file _/_v_a_r_/_l_i_b_/_d_p_k_g_/_s_t_a_t_u_s, are purged.

              Note: some configuration files might be unknown to ddppkkgg because they are created
              and handled separately through the configuration scripts.  In  that  case,  ddppkkgg
              won't remove them by itself, but the package's _p_o_s_t_r_m script (which is called by
              ddppkkgg), has to take care of their removal during  purge.  Of  course,  this  only
              applies  to  files  in  system  directories,  not configuration files written to
              individual users' home directories.

              Purging of a package consists of the following steps:

              11.. Remove the package,  if  not  already  removed.  See  ----rreemmoovvee  for  detailed
              information about how this is done.

              22.. Run _p_o_s_t_r_m script.

       --VV, ----vveerriiffyy [_p_a_c_k_a_g_e_-_n_a_m_e...]
              Verifies  the integrity of _p_a_c_k_a_g_e_-_n_a_m_e or all packages if omitted, by comparing
              information from the files installed  by  a  package  with  the  files  metadata
              information  stored in the ddppkkgg database (since dpkg 1.17.2).  The origin of the
              files metadata information in the database is the  binary  packages  themselves.
              That  metadata  gets  collected  at  package unpack time during the installation
              process.

              Currently the only functional check performed is an md5sum verification  of  the
              file  contents against the stored value in the files database.  It will only get
              checked if the database contains the file  md5sum.  To  check  for  any  missing
              metadata in the database, the ----aauuddiitt command can be used.

              The  output  format  is  selectable  with  the  ----vveerriiffyy--ffoorrmmaatt option, which by
              default uses the rrppmm format, but that might change in the future, and  as  such,
              programs  parsing  this  command output should be explicit about the format they
              expect.

       --CC, ----aauuddiitt [_p_a_c_k_a_g_e_-_n_a_m_e...]
              Performs database sanity and consistency checks for _p_a_c_k_a_g_e_-_n_a_m_e or all packages
              if  omitted  (per package checks since dpkg 1.17.10).  For example, searches for
              packages that have been installed only partially on your  system  or  that  have
              missing,  wrong  or obsolete control data or files. ddppkkgg will suggest what to do
              with them to get them fixed.

       ----uuppddaattee--aavvaaiill [_P_a_c_k_a_g_e_s_-_f_i_l_e]
       ----mmeerrggee--aavvaaiill [_P_a_c_k_a_g_e_s_-_f_i_l_e]
              Update ddppkkgg's and ddsseelleecctt's idea of which packages are  available.  With  action
              ----mmeerrggee--aavvaaiill,  old information is combined with information from _P_a_c_k_a_g_e_s_-_f_i_l_e.
              With action ----uuppddaattee--aavvaaiill, old information is replaced with the information  in
              the  _P_a_c_k_a_g_e_s_-_f_i_l_e.  The  _P_a_c_k_a_g_e_s_-_f_i_l_e  distributed with Debian is simply named
              «_P_a_c_k_a_g_e_s». If the _P_a_c_k_a_g_e_s_-_f_i_l_e argument is missing or named «--» then  it  will
              be  read  from  standard  input  (since  dpkg  1.17.7). ddppkkgg keeps its record of
              available packages in _/_v_a_r_/_l_i_b_/_d_p_k_g_/_a_v_a_i_l_a_b_l_e.

              A simpler one-shot command to retrieve and update the _a_v_a_i_l_a_b_l_e file is  ddsseelleecctt
              uuppddaattee.  Note  that  this file is mostly useless if you don't use ddsseelleecctt but an
              APT-based frontend: APT has its own system to keep track of available packages.

       --AA, ----rreeccoorrdd--aavvaaiill _p_a_c_k_a_g_e_-_f_i_l_e...
              Update ddppkkgg and ddsseelleecctt's idea of which packages are available with  information
              from  the  package  _p_a_c_k_a_g_e_-_f_i_l_e.  If  ----rreeccuurrssiivvee  or  --RR  option is specified,
              _p_a_c_k_a_g_e_-_f_i_l_e must refer to a directory instead.

       ----ffoorrggeett--oolldd--uunnaavvaaiill
              Now  oobbssoolleettee  and  a  no-op  as  ddppkkgg  will  automatically  forget  uninstalled
              unavailable  packages  (since  dpkg  1.15.4), but only those that do not contain
              user information such as package selections.

       ----cclleeaarr--aavvaaiill
              Erase the existing information about what packages are available.

       ----ggeett--sseelleeccttiioonnss [_p_a_c_k_a_g_e_-_n_a_m_e_-_p_a_t_t_e_r_n...]
              Get list of package selections, and write it to stdout. Without a pattern,  non-
              installed  packages  (i.e.  those which have been previously purged) will not be
              shown.

       ----sseett--sseelleeccttiioonnss
              Set package selections using file read from stdin. This file should  be  in  the
              format “_p_a_c_k_a_g_e _s_t_a_t_e”, where state is one of iinnssttaallll, hhoolldd, ddeeiinnssttaallll or ppuurrggee.
              Blank lines and comment lines beginning with ‘##’ are also permitted.

              The _a_v_a_i_l_a_b_l_e file needs to  be  up-to-date  for  this  command  to  be  useful,
              otherwise   unknown   packages   will   be  ignored  with  a  warning.  See  the
              ----uuppddaattee--aavvaaiill and ----mmeerrggee--aavvaaiill commands for more information.

       ----cclleeaarr--sseelleeccttiioonnss
              Set the requested state of every non-essential package to deinstall (since  dpkg
              1.13.18).   This  is intended to be used immediately before ----sseett--sseelleeccttiioonnss, to
              deinstall any packages not in list given to ----sseett--sseelleeccttiioonnss.

       ----yyeett--ttoo--uunnppaacckk
              Searches for packages selected for installation, but which for some reason still
              haven't been installed.

              Note:  This  command  makes  use  of  both  the  available  file and the package
              selections.

       ----pprreeddeepp--ppaacckkaaggee
              Print a single package which  is  the  target  of  one  or  more  relevant  pre-
              dependencies and has itself no unsatisfied pre-dependencies.

              If  such  a package is present, output it as a Packages file entry, which can be
              massaged as appropriate.

              Note: This command makes  use  of  both  the  available  file  and  the  package
              selections.

              Returns 0 when a package is printed, 1 when no suitable package is available and
              2 on error.

       ----aadddd--aarrcchhiitteeccttuurree _a_r_c_h_i_t_e_c_t_u_r_e
              Add _a_r_c_h_i_t_e_c_t_u_r_e to  the  list  of  architectures  for  which  packages  can  be
              installed   without   using   ----ffoorrccee--aarrcchhiitteeccttuurree  (since  dpkg  1.16.2).   The
              architecture ddppkkgg is built for (i.e.  the  output  of  ----pprriinntt--aarrcchhiitteeccttuurree)  is
              always part of that list.

       ----rreemmoovvee--aarrcchhiitteeccttuurree _a_r_c_h_i_t_e_c_t_u_r_e
              Remove  _a_r_c_h_i_t_e_c_t_u_r_e  from  the  list of architectures for which packages can be
              installed  without  using  ----ffoorrccee--aarrcchhiitteeccttuurree  (since  dpkg  1.16.2).  If  the
              architecture  is  currently  in  use  in the database then the operation will be
              refused, except if ----ffoorrccee--aarrcchhiitteeccttuurree is specified. The architecture  ddppkkgg  is
              built  for  (i.e.  the output of ----pprriinntt--aarrcchhiitteeccttuurree) can never be removed from
              that list.

       ----pprriinntt--aarrcchhiitteeccttuurree
              Print architecture of packages ddppkkgg installs (for example, “i386”).

       ----pprriinntt--ffoorreeiiggnn--aarrcchhiitteeccttuurreess
              Print a newline-separated list of the extra architectures ddppkkgg is configured  to
              allow packages to be installed for (since dpkg 1.16.2).

       ----aasssseerrtt--_f_e_a_t_u_r_e
              Asserts  that  ddppkkgg supports the requested feature.  Returns 0 if the feature is
              fully supported, 1 if the feature is known but ddppkkgg cannot provide  support  for
              it  yet,  and  2  if  the  feature  is  unknown.  The current list of assertable
              features is:

              ssuuppppoorrtt--pprreeddeeppeennddss
                     Supports the PPrree--DDeeppeennddss field (since dpkg 1.1.0).

              wwoorrkkiinngg--eeppoocchh
                     Supports epochs in version strings (since dpkg 1.4.0.7).

              lloonngg--ffiilleennaammeess
                     Supports long filenames in ddeebb(5) archives (since dpkg 1.4.1.17).

              mmuullttii--ccoonnrreepp
                     Supports multiple CCoonnfflliiccttss and RReeppllaacceess (since dpkg 1.4.1.19).

              mmuullttii--aarrcchh
                     Supports multi-arch fields and semantics (since dpkg 1.16.2).

              vveerrssiioonneedd--pprroovviiddeess
                     Supports versioned PPrroovviiddeess (since dpkg 1.17.11).

       ----vvaalliiddaattee--_t_h_i_n_g _s_t_r_i_n_g
              Validate that the _t_h_i_n_g _s_t_r_i_n_g  has  a  correct  syntax  (since  dpkg  1.18.16).
              Returns  0  if  the  _s_t_r_i_n_g  is  valid,  1 if the _s_t_r_i_n_g is invalid but might be
              accepted in lax contexts, and 2 if the _s_t_r_i_n_g is invalid.  The current  list  of
              validatable _t_h_i_n_gs is:

              ppkkggnnaammee
                     Validates the given package name (since dpkg 1.18.16).

              ttrriiggnnaammee
                     Validates the given trigger name (since dpkg 1.18.16).

              aarrcchhnnaammee
                     Validates the given architecture name (since dpkg 1.18.16).

              vveerrssiioonn
                     Validates the given version (since dpkg 1.18.16).

       ----ccoommppaarree--vveerrssiioonnss _v_e_r_1 _o_p _v_e_r_2
              Compare version numbers, where _o_p is a binary operator. ddppkkgg returns true (00) if
              the specified condition is satisfied, and false (11)  otherwise.  There  are  two
              groups of operators, which differ in how they treat an empty _v_e_r_1 or _v_e_r_2. These
              treat an empty version as earlier than any version: lltt llee eeqq  nnee  ggee  ggtt.  These
              treat an empty version as later than any version: lltt--nnll llee--nnll ggee--nnll ggtt--nnll. These
              are provided only for compatibility with control file syntax: << <<<< <<== == >>== >>>> >>.
              The  <<  and  >>  operators  are obsolete and should nnoott be used, due to confusing
              semantics. To illustrate: 00..11 << 00..11 evaluates to true.

       --??, ----hheellpp
              Display a brief help message.

       ----ffoorrccee--hheellpp
              Give help about the ----ffoorrccee--_t_h_i_n_g options.

       --DDhh, ----ddeebbuugg==hheellpp
              Give help about debugging options.

       ----vveerrssiioonn
              Display ddppkkgg version information.

