       DDPPKKGG__MMAAIINNTTSSCCRRIIPPTT__PPAACCKKAAGGEE__RREEFFCCOOUUNNTT
              Defined by ddppkkgg on the maintainer script environment to  the  package  reference
              count,  i.e.  the  number  of  package  instances  with  a  state  greater  than
              nnoott--iinnssttaalllleedd (since dpkg 1.17.2).

       DDPPKKGG__MMAAIINNTTSSCCRRIIPPTT__AARRCCHH
              Defined by ddppkkgg on the maintainer script environment  to  the  architecture  the
              package got built for (since dpkg 1.15.4).

       DDPPKKGG__MMAAIINNTTSSCCRRIIPPTT__NNAAMMEE
              Defined  by  ddppkkgg on the maintainer script environment to the name of the script
              running, one of pprreeiinnsstt, ppoossttiinnsstt, pprreerrmm or ppoossttrrmm (since dpkg 1.15.7).

       DDPPKKGG__MMAAIINNTTSSCCRRIIPPTT__DDEEBBUUGG
              Defined by ddppkkgg on the maintainer script environment to a  value  (‘00’  or  ‘11’)
              noting  whether  debugging  has been requested (with the ----ddeebbuugg option) for the
              maintainer scripts (since dpkg 1.18.4).

FFIILLEESS
       _/_e_t_c_/_d_p_k_g_/_d_p_k_g_._c_f_g_._d_/_[_0_-_9_a_-_z_A_-_Z___-_]_*
              Configuration fragment files (since dpkg 1.15.4).

       _/_e_t_c_/_d_p_k_g_/_d_p_k_g_._c_f_g
              Configuration file with default options.

       _/_v_a_r_/_l_o_g_/_d_p_k_g_._l_o_g
              Default log file (see _/_e_t_c_/_d_p_k_g_/_d_p_k_g_._c_f_g and option ----lloogg).

       The other files listed below are in their default directories, see option ----aaddmmiinnddiirr to
       see how to change locations of these files.

       _/_v_a_r_/_l_i_b_/_d_p_k_g_/_a_v_a_i_l_a_b_l_e
              List of available packages.

       _/_v_a_r_/_l_i_b_/_d_p_k_g_/_s_t_a_t_u_s
              Statuses  of  available packages. This file contains information about whether a
              package is marked for removing or not, whether it is installed or not, etc.  See
              section IINNFFOORRMMAATTIIOONN AABBOOUUTT PPAACCKKAAGGEESS for more info.

              The  status  file  is  backed up daily in _/_v_a_r_/_b_a_c_k_u_p_s. It can be useful if it's
              lost or corrupted due to filesystems troubles.

       The format and contents of a binary package are described in ddeebb(5).

BBUUGGSS
       ----nnoo--aacctt usually gives less information than might be helpful.

EEXXAAMMPPLLEESS
       To list installed packages related to the editor vvii(1) (note that ddppkkgg--qquueerryy  does  not
       load  the  _a_v_a_i_l_a_b_l_e  file  anymore  by default, and the ddppkkgg--qquueerryy ----llooaadd--aavvaaiill option
       should be used instead for that):
            ddppkkgg --ll ''**vvii**''

       To see the entries in _/_v_a_r_/_l_i_b_/_d_p_k_g_/_a_v_a_i_l_a_b_l_e of two packages:
            ddppkkgg ----pprriinntt--aavvaaiill eellvviiss vviimm || lleessss

       To search the listing of packages yourself:
            lleessss //vvaarr//lliibb//ddppkkgg//aavvaaiillaabbllee

       To remove an installed elvis package:
            ddppkkgg --rr eellvviiss

       To install a package, you first need to find it in an archive or CDROM.  The  _a_v_a_i_l_a_b_l_e
       file shows that the vim package is in section eeddiittoorrss:
            ccdd //mmeeddiiaa//ccddrroomm//ppooooll//mmaaiinn//vv//vviimm
            ddppkkgg --ii vviimm__44..55--33..ddeebb

       To make a local copy of the package selection states:
            ddppkkgg ----ggeett--sseelleeccttiioonnss >>mmyysseelleeccttiioonnss

       You  might  transfer  this  file  to  another  computer,  and  after having updated the
       _a_v_a_i_l_a_b_l_e  file  there  with   your   package   manager   frontend   of   choice   (see
       https://wiki.debian.org/Teams/Dpkg/FAQ for more details), for example:
            aapptt--ccaacchhee dduummppaavvaaiill || ddppkkgg ----mmeerrggee--aavvaaiill
       or with dpkg 1.17.6 and earlier:
            aavvaaiill==``mmkktteemmpp``
            aapptt--ccaacchhee dduummppaavvaaiill >>""$$aavvaaiill""
            ddppkkgg ----mmeerrggee--aavvaaiill ""$$aavvaaiill""
            rrmm ""$$aavvaaiill""
       you can install it with:
            ddppkkgg ----cclleeaarr--sseelleeccttiioonnss
            ddppkkgg ----sseett--sseelleeccttiioonnss <<mmyysseelleeccttiioonnss

       Note that this will not actually install or remove anything, but just set the selection
       state on the requested packages. You will  need  some  other  application  to  actually
       download and install the requested packages. For example, run aapptt--ggeett ddsseelleecctt--uuppggrraaddee.

       Ordinarily,  you will find that ddsseelleecctt(1) provides a more convenient way to modify the
       package selection states.

AADDDDIITTIIOONNAALL FFUUNNCCTTIIOONNAALLIITTYY
       Additional functionality can be gained by installing any  of  the  following  packages:
       aapptt, aappttiittuuddee and ddeebbssuummss.

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       aappttiittuuddee(1), aapptt(1), ddsseelleecctt(1), ddppkkgg--ddeebb(1), ddppkkgg--qquueerryy(1), ddeebb(5), ddeebb--ccoonnttrrooll(5),
       ddppkkgg..ccffgg(5), and ddppkkgg--rreeccoonnffiigguurree(8).

